# Derivatives & Hedging Analyst (Superannuation Fund)

## Overview
Manages sophisticated hedging strategies to control market risks (currency, interest rates, equities) across multi-billion dollar portfolios, working within major Australian super funds.

## Core Responsibilities
- Implement currency hedging programs for foreign exchange exposure from international investments, typically managing 30-50% hedge ratios across major currency pairs
- Execute interest rate risk management using swaps, futures, and options to optimize duration and yield curve exposure within fixed income portfolios valued in billions
- Value and mark-to-market all derivative positions daily, validate counterparty pricing, calculate Greeks, and test hedge effectiveness for accurate portfolio reporting
- Manage counterparty relationships by negotiating ISDA agreements, monitoring credit risk, optimizing collateral arrangements, and maintaining competitive pricing
- Design and implement hedging strategies efficiently while minimizing transaction costs, operational complexity, and ensuring alignment with fund investment objectives
- Ensure regulatory compliance with APRA requirements, investment mandates, internal risk limits, and prepare performance attribution analysis for investment committees

## Key Skills Required

### Technical & Quantitative
- Deep understanding of derivative instruments including forwards, futures, swaps, options, and structured products
- Advanced Excel proficiency with VBA automation and complex financial modeling capabilities
- Bloomberg terminal expertise for pricing, market data analysis, and trade execution functions
- Programming ability in Python/R for data analysis and process automation (increasingly essential)

### Risk & Analytical
- Quantitative skills in probability, statistics, financial mathematics, and stochastic processes
- Risk metrics knowledge including VaR, stress testing, scenario analysis, and hedge effectiveness measurement
- Understanding of hedge accounting standards (AASB 9) and fair value measurement methodologies
- Derivative valuation and pricing model expertise including Black-Scholes and multi-factor models

### Interpersonal & Commercial
- Exceptional attention to detail and accuracy given costly implications of trade errors
- Clear communication with traders, counterparties, portfolio managers, and investment committees
- Strong stakeholder management skills to influence senior investment leaders and negotiate with banks
- Commercial judgment to balance hedging costs against risk reduction benefits for member outcomes

## Work Mode

### Analytical Work (50-60%)
Excel modeling of hedge positions, Bloomberg market data analysis, derivative valuation and Greek calculations, hedge effectiveness testing, performance attribution, and building strategic analysis for investment committee presentations.

### Operational Execution (25-30%)
Daily trade execution and confirmation, collateral management and margin calls, position reconciliation across multiple systems (custodian, accounting, counterparties), system data entry, documentation, and maintaining audit trails.

### Stakeholder Communication (10-15%)
Daily derivatives team meetings, weekly investment committee updates, monthly counterparty bank calls, presenting to portfolio managers, coordinating with risk and operations teams, and explaining complex concepts to non-specialists.

### Strategic Research (5-10%)
Evaluating new derivative products and hedging strategies, analyzing alternative approaches, reviewing academic literature on risk management, attending industry seminars, and conducting cost-benefit analyses for proposed programs.

## Workplace Culture
Collaborative institutional environment balancing quantitative rigor with practical implementation, typically 7:30am-6pm hours with strong work-life balance compared to banking, purpose-driven mission serving member retirement outcomes.

## Career Path
- Entry: Graduate/Junior Derivatives Analyst (0-2 years)
- Progression: Derivatives Analyst → Senior Analyst → Manager/Head of Derivatives → Head of Portfolio Implementation → CIO or Portfolio Manager roles

## Salary Range
- **Graduate/Junior Analyst (0-2 years)**: AU$70,000-90,000 base + AU$5,000-15,000 bonus
- **Derivatives Analyst (2-5 years)**: AU$90,000-130,000 base + AU$10,000-30,000 bonus
- **Senior Analyst (5-8 years)**: AU$130,000-180,000 base + AU$25,000-45,000 bonus
- **Manager/Head of Derivatives (8-12 years)**: AU$180,000-260,000 base + AU$45,000-80,000 bonus
- **Head of Portfolio Implementation (12+ years)**: AU$250,000-400,000+ base + AU$75,000-150,000+ bonus

*Note: Major funds (AustralianSuper, Australian Retirement Trust, HESTA) pay at higher ranges; compensation typically 60-70% of investment banking but with significantly better work-life balance*

